close_symbols: UT_StubTable (or other global storage of UT_StubTableEntry_t entries)
explanation:
For deciding whether any operations in UT_Stub_RegisterReturnType are dead (i.e. executed but removable without changing program behaviour) the analyzer must know which writes and calls have externally observable effects and which reads elsewhere depend on them. The listed symbols are needed for that reasoning:

- UT_StubTableEntry_t
  Needed to know the exact layout and semantic meaning of fields written in this function (FuncKey, EntryType, Data.Buff.BasePtr, Data.Buff.TotalSize, Data.Buff.Position, Data.Buff.ContentTypeStr, ModeFlags). If those fields are never read by other code, writes could be dead; if they are read, they are live.

- UT_StubTable (or other global storage of UT_StubTableEntry_t entries)
  Needed to determine whether the entries persisted by this function are used later (i.e. whether setting up an entry has a program-visible effect). Also required to check whether UT_GetStubEntry/UT_ClearStubEntry operate on shared/global state.

- UT_GetStubEntry
  This function is called to find an existing return buffer entry or an unused slot. Its semantics determine whether the initial UT_GetStubEntry call (and the subsequent logic based on its return value) is necessary. For example, whether UT_GetStubEntry can return an existing buffer reused elsewhere, or if it always returns NULL, affects whether branches are live.

- UT_ClearStubEntry
  Called when sizes differ. Must know whether it has side effects (freeing memory, updating global tables, notifying other code). If UT_ClearStubEntry performs meaningful actions other than local housekeeping, the call is not dead.

- UT_Stub_GetReturnValuePtr
  One of the primary consumers of the return-buffer entry. Knowing whether this (or similar) routine reads BasePtr, Position, TotalSize, ContentTypeStr, or ModeFlags determines whether allocating/initializing those fields here is required for correct behaviour.

- UT_ExecuteBasicHandler
  Representative of the code paths that will actually use the stub entries for returning data during tests. Understanding how handlers interact with the stub entry determines whether setup in RegisterReturnType (allocating, zeroing, setting Position/type) is necessary.

- UT_SetDataBuffer and UT_GetDataBuffer
  These utilities are other potential consumers of the Data.Buff fields. If they read fields set here, those writes are meaningful; if they never read them, those writes may be dead.

- UT_EntryType enum / macros: UT_ENTRYTYPE_RETURN_BUFFER, UT_ENTRYTYPE_UNUSED
  Needed to know the precise meanings of the entry type values passed to UT_GetStubEntry and assigned to EntryType; the liveness of assigning EntryType depends on how other code interprets it.

- UT_MODEFLAG_ALLOC_BUF
  The function sets this flag after malloc; analyzer must know what this flag indicates (e.g. that buffer should be freed by Clear or other code). If no other code checks this flag, setting it might be dead; if other code relies on it for correct freeing/behaviour, it is required.

- UT_MAX_FUNC_STUBS
  Mentioned in the abort message and relevant to whether UT_GetStubEntry can legitimately return NULL when allocating a new entry. This affects whether the UtAssert_Abort branch is reachable and meaningful.

- UtAssert_Abort
  The abort call has program-global observable effect (terminating the test/program). Its semantics (does it longjmp/exit/log only?) matter for whether the error-handling branches are considered live.

- malloc
  Allocation has observable effects (resource usage, pointer identity). Knowing whether malloc is necessary (or ever fails) affects whether the malloc + error path + memset + flag set sequence are live.

- memset
  The zero-initialization of the allocated buffer can be relevant to program behaviour if subsequent reads assume zeroed memory. The analyzer must know whether later code relies on that initialization.

In summary, to judge whether each statement in UT_Stub_RegisterReturnType is removable without changing program behaviour, the analyzer needs the data-structure layout, the semantics/side-effects of the UT_* helper functions that read or modify those same structures, the meaning of the entry-type and mode-flag constants, and the behavior of allocation/assertion routines. The symbols above provide that necessary context.
